Fix for Orange paths

SimpleCV prompts this:

WARNING: I'm sorry, but you need the orange machine learning library
installed to use this

However orange library is installed, but system paths are not
correctly set. Importing `Orange` with capital O, and then `orange`
fixes the issue, so SimpleCV can use it.

Always check for the return value of cv.QueryFrame()

When grabbing frames from a video file, we have to check
the return value of cv.QueryFrame() in order to understand
whether the video is ended or not. Currently, SimpleCV
gives an exception when the video is over. See issue #135

They weren't working as intended with color pictures and scalars. Example:
Image((100,100))+100 should yield an image that's gray now. Before it only added to the blue channel.

I guess there's probably a need for adding tuples to the image, but I didn't really need that atm. Though i still think this is a better behavoir for the

Image.save() and ImageSet.save() save images for 'notebook' so that
they are removed when the object is destroyed.

Fix Image.save() and ImageSet.save() for Windows environment.

Image.save() and ImageSet.save() use Image.save(temp=True) for
saving temporary files for notebook instead of generating paths of
them manually. The function had not worked well on Windows
environment because it had generated invalid (at least on Windows)
paths by simply adding '/tmp/' as a prefix.

Put variables in quotations for the command 'SETX' in 'install.bat'.

For the command 'SETX' in 'scripts/install/win/install.bat',
variables are put in quotations. Without quotation, the command
shell misinterprets the argument as multiple arguments if the
variables include a white space. It causes an error that the command
does nothing.

Modified the ImageClass to properly call the HaarDetectObjects function as
described in the docs.

Before it was missing minNeighbors and minSize, minNeighbors was being set by
the cv canny edge flag (0) which, only due to coincidence (cv flag enum being
0) worked, but had the effect of always setting minNeighbors to 0, making for
many false positives.

Here's the full method signature, which I call in the code
HaarDetectObjects(image, cascade, storage, scaleFactor=1.1, minNeighbors=3,
flags=0, minSize=(0, 0))

see: http://opencv.willowgarage.com/documentation/python/objdetect_cascade_classification.html
